1
00:00:01,240 --> 00:00:02,660
Hi everyone.

2
00:00:03,040 --> 00:00:08,880
Today I'll show how to build a controlled Kacher circuit for our systems.

3
00:00:09,880 --> 00:00:12,740
The circuit came out working.

4
00:00:13,560 --> 00:00:24,640
Modulation of the circuit can be done by pulse, set by duty cycle at frequencies from 0.1 Hz to 50 kHz.

5
00:00:24,640 --> 00:00:41,420
While running on the Kacher circuit — that is, switching the high-voltage Tesla coil with feedback from the cold end to the transistor base.

6
00:00:42,020 --> 00:00:51,920
Or up to 100 kHz, if this circuit is used as a switch for an active load — for example, an incandescent lamp.

7
00:00:53,580 --> 00:01:00,340
Here you can see the divider resistor values are marked.

8
00:01:01,160 --> 00:01:02,580
Values in parentheses.

9
00:01:03,620 --> 00:01:05,160
The resistors are picked this way.

10
00:01:05,520 --> 00:01:12,280
This is for those who'll build the system as a switch for an active load.

11
00:01:12,280 --> 00:01:38,160
With 350 Ω and 740 Ω, the system creates a 4.7 V bias on the transistor base — if we measure the voltage with the base disconnected from the 2SC5200 transistor.

12
00:01:38,160 --> 00:01:49,720
That is, this divider creates 4.7 V at the applied supply voltage of 15 V in this system.

13
00:01:50,520 --> 00:01:51,640
The value in parentheses.

14
00:01:52,260 --> 00:02:07,020
And our main value, which will work on the Kacher circuit similar to the previous circuit I showed, is 3.3 kΩ.

15
00:02:11,260 --> 00:02:30,900
The chain through which the Kacher is powered is the same, and in this system it's shown — except here a DC-to-elevated-DC converter is drawn, the so-called DC-DC converter.

16
00:02:30,900 --> 00:02:33,940
DC-DC converter.

17
00:02:35,400 --> 00:02:42,260
I also showed its schematic in my videos — 12 V input, output adjustable from 50 to 200 V.

18
00:02:42,900 --> 00:02:59,620
This Kacher circuit starts in controlled mode at about 10 V of supply voltage at this point, and I tested it up to 100 V.

19
00:02:59,620 --> 00:03:08,040
In particular, our transistor is operational up to 200 V — that's the main power switch.

20
00:03:09,860 --> 00:03:26,080
The circuit is fully compatible with the one I also showed — see the "BTG controller" video — except for one moment.

21
00:03:28,020 --> 00:03:35,960
Here's how compatibility happens — to the same connector — and the link goes here to control too.

22
00:03:36,680 --> 00:03:50,260
The moment is, for controlling the Tesla that runs in controlled pulse mode, we needed a pulse of this shape.

23
00:03:50,260 --> 00:03:57,280
A long signal with a small pause between them.

24
00:03:57,360 --> 00:04:06,520
That pause for the controlled Tesla set the operating mode — formed those bursts.

25
00:04:06,800 --> 00:04:11,560
By the logic of operation, we covered this in previous videos too.

26
00:04:12,400 --> 00:04:20,100
For the Kacher this isn't suitable, so for them to be compatible, we need to remove one inversion.

27
00:04:20,260 --> 00:04:35,600
In this case, to do that, we connect not to pin 10 of the chip, which goes to the control block output, but to pin 11.

28
00:04:35,680 --> 00:04:46,420
That is, we remove one inverted signal, and then we get a signal of this shape at the chip's input.

29
00:04:46,420 --> 00:04:55,240
And by changing its duty cycle, we can set the on-time of the controlled Kacher circuit.

30
00:04:56,240 --> 00:05:07,480
To implement this controlled Kacher circuit, we'll need two chips — one of them the IR2113 driver, already familiar from previous videos.

31
00:05:08,700 --> 00:05:14,740
It's a two-channel driver that doesn't insert dead time between control signals.

32
00:05:14,740 --> 00:05:18,100
And a TC4093 chip.

33
00:05:20,420 --> 00:05:27,800
That's four Schmitt triggers with 2-input AND-NOT (inverting) outputs.

34
00:05:28,800 --> 00:05:37,400
That is, 2-AND-NOT logic combined with Schmitt triggers in one chip.

35
00:05:38,400 --> 00:05:40,680
A few resistors.

36
00:05:40,860 --> 00:05:53,740
Pay special attention to the resistors that create the bias on the gate of the P-channel transistor.

37
00:05:53,920 --> 00:06:03,900
Because a P-channel transistor needs a negative voltage potential on its gate to control it.

38
00:06:03,900 --> 00:06:10,340
And N-channel transistors are controlled by positive potential.

39
00:06:10,400 --> 00:06:11,380
They're simpler.

40
00:06:12,020 --> 00:06:19,100
With P-channel you have to build a system that drives it with negative voltage specifically.

41
00:06:19,740 --> 00:06:30,740
This divider ultimately sets the consumption and stability of the circuit.

42
00:06:31,740 --> 00:06:46,960
The divider on the gate of the RF4905 transistor is picked so the controlling negative voltage is about 14.7 V.

43
00:06:47,180 --> 00:06:57,080
Like N-channel transistors, P-channel can be controlled by voltages up to 20 V.

44
00:06:57,080 --> 00:07:20,120
But most importantly, this divider is picked so that during operation this transistor increases the signal time relative to the time coming from the drain of the N-channel control transistor.

45
00:07:20,120 --> 00:07:20,820
Control transistor.

46
00:07:21,280 --> 00:07:23,620
That's one feature of this circuit.

47
00:07:23,620 --> 00:07:29,660
We'll also need a fast-acting Schottky diode — in this case SR510.

48
00:07:30,520 --> 00:07:36,820
And of course, the 2SC5200 and two N-channel transistors.

49
00:07:38,060 --> 00:07:42,560
Now let's go through the logic of this circuit.

50
00:07:43,820 --> 00:07:50,840
I made a drawing that'll make it easier to understand how the circuit works.

51
00:07:53,980 --> 00:08:05,160
Per the schematic: driver, ATS4093 chip, and the switches schematically shown in the circuit.

52
00:08:05,840 --> 00:08:09,800
This is transistor 1, transistor 2, transistor 3, and the main one, 4.

53
00:08:10,100 --> 00:08:14,040
It's not shown here — it doesn't participate in the action logic, it's just power.

54
00:08:15,220 --> 00:08:15,780
Watching.

55
00:08:16,360 --> 00:08:22,660
The control signal comes in with some duty cycle we set on an external generator.

56
00:08:23,620 --> 00:08:38,400
It hits the first driver channel directly — its output goes from pin 1 to transistor 2.

57
00:08:38,860 --> 00:08:48,280
Transistor 2 in our case is the one controlling the P-channel FET.

58
00:08:49,280 --> 00:08:53,820
Now we'll analyze the action logic.

59
00:08:53,980 --> 00:09:14,660
But to control transistor 1, which shorts the power transistor's base to minus, we route its control through the logic elements of the TC4093 chip.

60
00:09:14,660 --> 00:09:16,740
Why is this done?

61
00:09:16,900 --> 00:09:28,180
To create some time delay through several inversions — we work with the lag of the chip's logic elements.

62
00:09:28,200 --> 00:09:30,900
To shift signals in time.

63
00:09:31,660 --> 00:09:39,700
Let's analyze what happens directly at the driver outputs after we fed in this signal.

64
00:09:39,700 --> 00:09:48,120
At pin 7 a signal forms with lag, at pin 1 a signal without lag.

65
00:09:48,300 --> 00:10:00,580
At pin 1 the signal that arrived at the input leads the signal that appeared after processing by the chip's logic elements.

66
00:10:00,580 --> 00:10:10,940
It's schematically shown that the signal at pin 1 leads the one at pin 7 of the driver chip.

67
00:10:11,680 --> 00:10:15,080
Next, the signal reaches the transistors.

68
00:10:16,600 --> 00:10:18,100
They're marked here.

69
00:10:18,540 --> 00:10:19,660
And what happens here?

70
00:10:19,800 --> 00:10:29,320
You have to understand that FETs have properties similar to logic elements — they invert the signal.

71
00:10:29,320 --> 00:10:31,440
Examining this process.

72
00:10:31,680 --> 00:10:35,520
We had this signal on transistor 2, it got inverted.

73
00:10:36,120 --> 00:10:46,480
It transformed — our shaded signal — at the same time the signal on transistor 1 also inverted to this signal.

74
00:10:46,480 --> 00:11:00,480
But the time between them — the lag — was preserved, since these transistors are the same part number, so their delay times match.

75
00:11:01,380 --> 00:11:03,260
Transistors from the same series.

76
00:11:05,120 --> 00:11:13,960
So far we preserve the lag time only thanks to the 4093 chip's elements.

77
00:11:13,960 --> 00:11:21,280
Next, the signal from transistor 2 goes through a resistor divider to transistor 3.

78
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:34,380
And the resistor divider is picked so that on transistor 3, marked "duty cycle grows," it increases the duty cycle of this signal.

79
00:11:34,380 --> 00:11:38,640
It inverts our shaded signal.

80
00:11:39,480 --> 00:11:45,180
But at the same time as inverting, it also stretches it out in time.

81
00:11:45,700 --> 00:11:57,780
While transistor 1 leaves the signal inverted, but the time relative to the input signal — its time doesn't change.

82
00:11:57,780 --> 00:12:15,200
And if you stand at these points with a dual-channel oscilloscope, you'll clearly see the signal at transistor 3's drain has lengthened relative to the input.

83
00:12:15,580 --> 00:12:19,100
You'll also notice the time shift.

84
00:12:20,420 --> 00:12:26,040
This is done so the transistors work with overlap.

85
00:12:26,040 --> 00:12:33,040
We artificially create what's called shoot-through between the two transistors.

86
00:12:33,600 --> 00:12:44,500
In this case it isn't dangerous, because the transistors operate in shoot-through mode through a resistor and diode.

87
00:12:44,640 --> 00:12:53,460
That is, this resistance converts the shoot-through current into heat over time.

88
00:12:53,460 --> 00:12:56,760
The transistor doesn't heat up too strongly.

89
00:12:56,840 --> 00:13:04,100
I recommend putting 2-watt resistors in these chains.

90
00:13:05,000 --> 00:13:07,780
Discharge resistors of 1 W are fine.

91
00:13:08,240 --> 00:13:12,220
And here you can also use 1 W resistors.

92
00:13:13,220 --> 00:13:19,300
So, if we move to the next points.

93
00:13:19,520 --> 00:13:21,360
Drew the oscillograms here.

94
00:13:22,140 --> 00:13:28,420
Disconnect transistor 1 from the resistor divider.

95
00:13:28,480 --> 00:13:30,000
We'll see this signal.

96
00:13:30,180 --> 00:13:33,180
Its shape here is exactly this.

97
00:13:34,460 --> 00:13:40,360
This is the control signal coming out of the drain of transistor 3.

98
00:13:40,360 --> 00:13:42,520
That is, from our P-channel transistor.

99
00:13:43,120 --> 00:13:49,280
It has this edge and some drop, but it's longer in time.

100
00:13:50,280 --> 00:13:57,440
And now look at the signal coming out of transistor 1's drain.

101
00:13:58,280 --> 00:14:04,240
It has a delay since we formed it here, this delay.

102
00:14:05,080 --> 00:14:10,160
And its leading edge lands at this point.

103
00:14:10,360 --> 00:14:14,320
That's the moment this transistor opens.

104
00:14:15,300 --> 00:14:19,260
A period of time where the transistors work with overlap.

105
00:14:19,820 --> 00:14:24,340
And actually our signal takes this shape.

106
00:14:25,220 --> 00:14:26,740
This is the shape we want.

107
00:14:27,500 --> 00:14:30,680
A smooth rising point.

108
00:14:31,120 --> 00:14:37,120
The transistor handles it really well and works great in switching mode.

109
00:14:37,120 --> 00:14:41,020
Don't worry about this rising edge.

110
00:14:41,660 --> 00:14:45,360
Especially when the system runs in Kacher mode.

111
00:14:47,460 --> 00:14:51,460
It doesn't really matter what this edge looks like.

112
00:14:51,540 --> 00:14:58,080
Because the Kacher, like any Tesla coil, takes some time to ramp up to its max.

113
00:14:58,080 --> 00:15:02,680
Even that brief time is enough for it to ramp up.

114
00:15:02,680 --> 00:15:10,540
And moreover, this gentle edge only shows up from 40 kHz and higher.

115
00:15:11,360 --> 00:15:16,960
At lower frequencies it's practically square.

116
00:15:19,200 --> 00:15:23,500
So why did we add this overlap?

117
00:15:23,780 --> 00:15:28,960
First, the overlap lets us cut this resistor out of the circuit.

118
00:15:28,960 --> 00:15:35,020
And sharply pull the base of our power switch to minus.

119
00:15:35,220 --> 00:15:39,420
Since the switch is N-channel by conductivity.

120
00:15:40,300 --> 00:15:45,200
A negative voltage potential on its base closes it sharply.

121
00:15:46,040 --> 00:15:50,840
This switch also plays a very important role.

122
00:15:51,640 --> 00:15:54,360
It prevents the Kacher from starting up.

123
00:15:54,360 --> 00:16:05,720
In the sense that the common minus conductor is also the grounding wire.

124
00:16:05,860 --> 00:16:10,040
Since grounding is connected to the transistor emitter.

125
00:16:11,380 --> 00:16:18,780
And so this transistor not only excludes this resistor.

126
00:16:18,780 --> 00:16:21,820
It also pulls the base to minus.

127
00:16:21,960 --> 00:16:27,070
And connects the cold end of the Tesla directly to grounding.

128
00:16:28,080 --> 00:16:38,220
And any subsequent oscillations that could trigger the power switch to self-generate can't reach the base.

129
00:16:38,220 --> 00:16:45,480
Because the base-emitter junction of the power switch has some resistance.

130
00:16:46,260 --> 00:16:53,520
Which is larger than the resistance of the open FET switch.

131
00:16:54,220 --> 00:17:01,100
And so the grounding ends up short-circuited with the cold end of the high-voltage coil.

132
00:17:01,720 --> 00:17:07,880
And no oscillations can make this transistor work in self-generating mode.

133
00:17:09,160 --> 00:17:18,440
The only thing you can see when working at high frequencies from 20 to 50 kHz —

134
00:17:18,540 --> 00:17:29,680
if your high-voltage Kacher coil has a good Q-factor, you can observe the ramp-up moment.

135
00:17:29,760 --> 00:17:33,140
Which we'll look at further in the oscillograms — up to maximum.

136
00:17:33,160 --> 00:17:34,660
And then a decay tail.

137
00:17:34,660 --> 00:17:44,500
And if the modulation is close enough in time at frequencies above 20 kHz.

138
00:17:44,700 --> 00:17:52,540
Then you can see the decay tail overlap with the rising edge.

139
00:17:52,680 --> 00:18:00,300
At that moment the Kacher isn't running anymore, but thanks to its Q-factor, decaying oscillations still exist in it.

140
00:18:00,300 --> 00:18:07,200
But with this circuit, decaying oscillations are only the free ones.

141
00:18:07,500 --> 00:18:11,540
The Kacher isn't running at this moment, consuming nothing.

142
00:18:12,840 --> 00:18:15,360
Let's examine the circuit solutions.

143
00:18:16,260 --> 00:18:28,700
In this case you can see the chain feeding power to the power switch stayed the same as in the previous ordinary Kacher circuit.

144
00:18:28,700 --> 00:18:31,680
It's shown on this schematic.

145
00:18:33,080 --> 00:18:34,040
This is the chain.

146
00:18:35,540 --> 00:18:38,160
Here are the input terminals.

147
00:18:39,500 --> 00:18:43,920
Plus and minus power connections.

148
00:18:44,780 --> 00:18:45,400
Capacitor.

149
00:18:45,800 --> 00:18:48,880
Then the filter with counter windings.

150
00:18:49,120 --> 00:18:50,080
Then another capacitor.

151
00:18:50,220 --> 00:18:52,660
The main reservoir electrolytic.

152
00:18:53,420 --> 00:18:57,120
And the high-frequency film cap.

153
00:18:57,120 --> 00:18:59,360
We covered this part.

154
00:19:00,360 --> 00:19:08,160
And to this board I added another board that controls our power switch.

155
00:19:08,660 --> 00:19:11,180
The switch is on the heat sink.

156
00:19:12,080 --> 00:19:13,460
You can clearly see it.

157
00:19:13,720 --> 00:19:14,560
Screwed in here.

158
00:19:15,020 --> 00:19:19,840
The heat sink for it is overkill.

159
00:19:20,140 --> 00:19:21,820
It doesn't heat up that much.

160
00:19:23,620 --> 00:19:25,800
You can use a smaller one.

161
00:19:25,800 --> 00:19:27,980
So, what do we see here?

162
00:19:28,340 --> 00:19:34,040
Our chip that creates the time delay, TC4093.

163
00:19:34,880 --> 00:19:36,300
Two-channel driver.

164
00:19:37,580 --> 00:19:40,560
Input wiring with filters.

165
00:19:41,120 --> 00:19:51,060
And here we have the main divider to the base of our power switch — 3.3 kΩ, 2.7 kΩ.

166
00:19:51,060 --> 00:19:55,420
SR510 Schottky diode.

167
00:19:56,380 --> 00:20:02,480
And here three transistors on a common heat sink.

168
00:20:03,960 --> 00:20:08,300
They heat up a bit, so I put them on a heat sink.

169
00:20:08,700 --> 00:20:10,440
Could be on a smaller individual one.

170
00:20:11,260 --> 00:20:15,020
Heating isn't significant but it's there.

171
00:20:15,020 --> 00:20:25,520
As a more solid build, it's soldered to the prototyping board itself.

172
00:20:26,280 --> 00:20:32,700
That is, minimal parts, the system runs, and power goes to the inductor.

173
00:20:33,380 --> 00:20:43,160
Instead of the inductor, as I said, you can connect an active load and use the circuit just in switching mode.

174
00:20:44,160 --> 00:20:52,260
Now we'll connect the circuit to the Kacher and see what it can do in action.

175
00:20:52,560 --> 00:20:53,560
So, the rig is assembled.

176
00:20:54,220 --> 00:20:59,340
Grounding is connected, because grounding plays an important role for this system.

177
00:21:00,880 --> 00:21:02,140
Power connected.

178
00:21:02,460 --> 00:21:07,550
Power from two separate lab supplies.

179
00:21:07,550 --> 00:21:10,650
One is set at 15 V.

180
00:21:10,810 --> 00:21:20,010
Right now you can see logic-part consumption with no signal applied at the input.

181
00:21:20,890 --> 00:21:28,890
Here we'll change the supply voltage with this trim pot and watch consumption.

182
00:21:30,390 --> 00:21:36,830
The signal will come directly from a lab signal generator.

183
00:21:36,830 --> 00:21:40,150
It's now in pulse mode.

184
00:21:40,630 --> 00:21:44,690
Pulse amplitude is 10 V.

185
00:21:45,770 --> 00:21:53,470
With 10% duty cycle on the positive half-period.

186
00:21:55,630 --> 00:21:59,250
We'll watch the oscillograms on the oscilloscope.

187
00:22:00,250 --> 00:22:05,670
Main power for the power switch is applied at this point.

188
00:22:06,110 --> 00:22:07,810
And then goes to the circuit.

189
00:22:08,510 --> 00:22:10,370
Circuit is running.

190
00:22:10,610 --> 00:22:17,250
Stable operation kicks in at a 17% duty cycle on the control signal.

191
00:22:18,070 --> 00:22:23,950
Now in this case 10 kHz for ease of viewing the signal.

192
00:22:23,950 --> 00:22:31,290
The logic side doesn't draw much.

193
00:22:31,510 --> 00:22:39,430
And here's the supply voltage and current consumption at which the system entered stable oscillation.

194
00:22:40,730 --> 00:22:46,210
Now you can see the field around the system isn't too big.

195
00:22:47,150 --> 00:22:52,850
When you touch a neon bulb to it, it lights up.

196
00:22:52,850 --> 00:22:59,190
The oscilloscope probe is nearby and we can watch the oscillogram.

197
00:23:01,570 --> 00:23:08,350
How the Kacher runs at this supply voltage.

198
00:23:08,790 --> 00:23:11,990
You see the Q-factor is very high.

199
00:23:13,030 --> 00:23:20,570
You can also see the additional wave that does some amplitude modulation in the system.

200
00:23:21,570 --> 00:23:25,690
And we'll experiment with interesting things.

201
00:23:25,750 --> 00:23:31,870
If you bring a hand close to the high-voltage coil, watch how the system reacts.

202
00:23:32,930 --> 00:23:41,510
For a full test, now we raise the supply voltage of our system.

203
00:23:43,010 --> 00:23:47,330
For example — yeah, runs confidently.

204
00:23:48,290 --> 00:23:50,270
Feeding 55 V.

205
00:23:51,930 --> 00:23:54,890
The current draw went up a bit.

206
00:23:56,010 --> 00:23:58,070
The signal is naturally off the chart.

207
00:24:02,140 --> 00:24:10,100
And you can already hear a little spark at the antenna tip.

208
00:24:10,100 --> 00:24:16,400
Now you can hear the sound at a 10 Hz rate.

209
00:24:18,620 --> 00:24:23,320
Try increasing the duty cycle of the control pulse.

210
00:24:27,130 --> 00:24:31,090
Increasing the duty cycle, watching the oscillogram change.

211
00:24:32,650 --> 00:24:39,250
Now you can see consumption growing with the duty cycle.

212
00:24:39,250 --> 00:24:51,430
You can see the little spark has become powerful — stretching to 1.2–1.5 cm.

213
00:24:53,030 --> 00:24:59,750
Watch the oscillogram — the operating time in our system is growing.

214
00:25:00,870 --> 00:25:05,170
Raise the control pulse duty cycle further.

215
00:25:07,650 --> 00:25:15,470
Now we'll set the control pulse to 40% duty cycle.

216
00:25:18,430 --> 00:25:20,930
The oscillogram has this shape.

217
00:25:21,470 --> 00:25:27,610
But this mode isn't useful for our system anymore because the duty cycle is too big.

218
00:25:28,370 --> 00:25:32,770
Visually you can see the little spark has gotten very powerful.

219
00:25:32,770 --> 00:25:37,790
You can see the neon bulb glowing at a big distance.

220
00:25:39,250 --> 00:25:42,910
And it lights up very well at this frequency.

221
00:25:44,210 --> 00:25:53,090
By the way, you can build a singing Tesla out of this circuit that plays a MIDI file.

222
00:25:54,330 --> 00:25:58,070
I'll show this now by changing the frequency.

223
00:25:58,310 --> 00:25:59,410
You can hear the sound.

224
00:26:02,770 --> 00:26:05,930
Now we have 3 kHz.

225
00:26:06,370 --> 00:26:14,150
And you can hear the sound the little spark of the system emits.

226
00:26:17,110 --> 00:26:21,470
You see — it works at 3 kHz.

227
00:26:22,890 --> 00:26:24,610
We can shift.

228
00:26:26,870 --> 00:26:28,950
1 kHz.

229
00:26:29,210 --> 00:26:30,070
Tonal sound.

230
00:26:33,670 --> 00:26:36,150
Changing the frequency.

231
00:26:36,830 --> 00:26:40,690
And it goes into the inaudible range.

232
00:26:42,390 --> 00:26:46,410
Now 25 kHz control frequency.

233
00:26:47,790 --> 00:26:52,670
And you can see the Kacher confidently modulating.

234
00:26:53,710 --> 00:26:59,030
Drop the duty cycle to 30%.

235
00:26:59,030 --> 00:27:01,950
The system runs stably.

236
00:27:03,090 --> 00:27:05,550
Little spark is pretty powerful.

237
00:27:07,670 --> 00:27:11,470
At 30%, at 25 kHz frequency.

238
00:27:13,170 --> 00:27:17,070
We have this voltage and current draw.

239
00:27:24,460 --> 00:27:28,260
Set the duty cycle to 20%.

240
00:27:28,940 --> 00:27:31,560
Consumption immediately dropped noticeably.

241
00:27:32,560 --> 00:27:37,060
Generally the system will run somewhere around this consumption.

242
00:27:37,180 --> 00:27:41,120
23–25% control pulse.

243
00:27:44,000 --> 00:27:46,600
You can see its full consumption.

244
00:27:51,170 --> 00:27:53,810
Now let's look at frequency capabilities.

245
00:27:56,870 --> 00:27:58,810
Now 25 kHz.

246
00:28:00,390 --> 00:28:02,850
35 kHz.

247
00:28:06,050 --> 00:28:08,070
45 kHz.

248
00:28:09,090 --> 00:28:14,130
You can see the system modulating.

249
00:28:15,930 --> 00:28:18,510
55 kHz.

250
00:28:21,790 --> 00:28:31,530
Operation stops at 55% because we need to add control pulse duty cycle.

251
00:28:32,410 --> 00:28:35,570
Raised the duty cycle to 35%.

252
00:28:35,570 --> 00:28:39,130
And the system started again.

253
00:28:39,930 --> 00:28:42,970
Wide adjustment range.

254
00:28:50,410 --> 00:28:55,330
Playing it in musical Tesla mode again.

255
00:29:01,690 --> 00:29:03,610
Really interesting thing.

256
00:29:04,440 --> 00:29:07,470
Now we can go into Hz.

257
00:29:11,450 --> 00:29:12,670
100 Hz.

258
00:29:13,670 --> 00:29:17,030
You can do 50 Hz for modulation.

259
00:29:17,770 --> 00:29:19,110
50 Hz.

260
00:29:19,390 --> 00:29:21,090
Now I'll show the oscillogram.

261
00:29:23,190 --> 00:29:27,530
There are bursts.

262
00:29:29,070 --> 00:29:35,190
You see — this shape.

263
00:29:37,450 --> 00:29:39,330
Lowering the duty cycle.

264
00:29:41,210 --> 00:29:42,450
15%.

265
00:29:42,450 --> 00:29:48,670
You can clearly hear the transformer sound.

266
00:29:49,190 --> 00:29:50,610
Same as it runs.

267
00:29:51,610 --> 00:29:59,030
It starts arcing to the metal object at 50 Hz.

268
00:30:00,550 --> 00:30:07,310
The circuit is really good even for experiments.

269
00:30:09,550 --> 00:30:15,950
For those who want to get familiar and build something like this.

270
00:30:17,270 --> 00:30:19,750
Interesting even just for demo.

271
00:30:45,800 --> 00:30:48,680
This sound is coming from the little spark.

272
00:30:59,080 --> 00:31:00,980
Enough playing.

273
00:31:01,360 --> 00:31:03,280
You'll assemble it and play with it.

274
00:31:03,780 --> 00:31:05,460
The thing is pretty cool.

275
00:31:07,460 --> 00:31:09,820
Turn off pulse delivery.

276
00:31:11,160 --> 00:31:13,080
Channel off.

277
00:31:14,720 --> 00:31:18,720
Only the logic-side consumption left.

278
00:31:19,300 --> 00:31:23,600
And you can see the power consumption.

279
00:31:24,600 --> 00:31:25,700
Amps at zero.

280
00:31:25,700 --> 00:31:29,000
Moving on to our specific tasks.

281
00:31:30,300 --> 00:31:35,740
Operation is maintained when connecting a fairly big antenna.

282
00:31:36,300 --> 00:31:45,760
We can also see that it sparks at the same modulation frequency on the antenna itself.

283
00:31:46,540 --> 00:31:50,600
The antenna sparks to a metal object.

284
00:31:51,580 --> 00:31:57,760
When the antenna is connected we observe a big diameter of the electric field.

285
00:31:57,900 --> 00:32:06,760
The neon bulb reacts at a pretty big distance from this system with the antenna.

286
00:32:08,580 --> 00:32:13,940
And now I wanted to point out an important feature of the Kacher circuit.

287
00:32:14,140 --> 00:32:17,500
I expanded to the carrier signal.

288
00:32:17,500 --> 00:32:20,880
You see a clean sine wave.

289
00:32:22,820 --> 00:32:24,160
Bringing in a hand.

290
00:32:24,460 --> 00:32:26,800
You see the frequency drifts.

291
00:32:28,760 --> 00:32:30,700
On the oscilloscope.

292
00:32:31,620 --> 00:32:38,660
The Kacher is a self-oscillator circuit with feedback to the transistor base.

293
00:32:38,660 --> 00:32:48,100
And in our system, it's useful that when the antenna is right above the system's inductor.

294
00:32:48,400 --> 00:32:53,160
The inductor's magnetic field creates a pickup on the antenna.

295
00:32:54,100 --> 00:33:02,520
And that voltage potential goes through the high-voltage coil to the base of our power transistor.

296
00:33:02,520 --> 00:33:11,580
This way the Kacher has one irreplaceable advantage over the controlled Tesla.

297
00:33:11,840 --> 00:33:18,840
Specifically for the so-called TL494 chip-glitch crowd.

298
00:33:19,900 --> 00:33:27,020
This effect — the feedback when you bring a hand close.

299
00:33:27,240 --> 00:33:30,800
It also works with pickup from the inductor.

300
00:33:30,800 --> 00:33:40,520
And it turns out the Kacher makes it easier to phase-tune between the low-side frequencies.

301
00:33:42,100 --> 00:33:46,480
What happens in the push-pull inductor circuit.

302
00:33:46,980 --> 00:33:51,060
And our high-voltage, high-frequency system.

303
00:33:52,140 --> 00:33:53,840
Exactly because it's a self-oscillator.

304
00:33:55,000 --> 00:33:58,140
Unfortunately, the controlled Tesla doesn't let you do this.

305
00:33:58,140 --> 00:34:00,880
You have to correct that moment manually.

306
00:34:01,040 --> 00:34:09,140
So all other things being equal, working on the Kacher makes system startup easier.

307
00:34:11,560 --> 00:34:21,920
Another thing — you can clearly see the Kacher rings.

308
00:34:22,760 --> 00:34:27,340
The signal you see now reached maximum.

309
00:34:27,580 --> 00:34:33,980
Even if we now change the control signal duty cycle, say to 20%.

310
00:34:34,600 --> 00:34:42,700
You also see that when the system has good Q-factor, the tail of this ring is pretty big.

311
00:34:43,380 --> 00:34:45,460
How do we get rid of it in the system?

312
00:34:46,460 --> 00:34:54,180
We see we have a ramp-up to maximum and then a drop.

313
00:34:55,300 --> 00:35:03,000
To get rid of this tail, you can just apply a common circuit solution.

314
00:35:03,080 --> 00:35:09,240
Here at the antenna tip, where the little spark to the metal object is.

315
00:35:10,120 --> 00:35:12,440
Add a spark gap to ground.

316
00:35:13,300 --> 00:35:22,240
And by adjusting the gap distance, achieve this.

317
00:35:22,260 --> 00:35:24,280
Look at the oscillogram.

318
00:35:24,760 --> 00:35:31,440
You can see — bringing the metal object close and the ring disappears.

319
00:35:32,780 --> 00:35:36,400
The ring goes away in our system.

320
00:35:37,400 --> 00:35:45,060
Now I'll try to tune more precisely so you can see this moment.

321
00:35:54,250 --> 00:35:57,050
You can clearly see the ring being cut.

322
00:35:58,090 --> 00:36:03,430
And here with the spark gap, you can really effectively cut this whole tail.

323
00:36:03,430 --> 00:36:12,750
By the way, the spark gap will also regulate the final amplitude at the high-voltage terminal.

324
00:36:15,210 --> 00:36:18,850
Good luck to everyone with your experiments — all the best, keep going.
